		{"id":"img-var1-ad12","type":"file","file":"Elevate/00 Assets/T003/David_Ad_12/Var1/variant-1.png","x":2000,"y":660,"width":399,"height":500},
		{"id":"text-var1-ad12","type":"text","text":"**Variation 1**\nPersona Life (Native): Close-up of car steering wheel, pharmacy bag on seat.","x":2000,"y":1180,"width":400,"height":100},
		{"id":"img-var2-ad12","type":"file","file":"Elevate/00 Assets/T003/David_Ad_12/Var2/variant-1.png","x":2450,"y":660,"width":399,"height":500},
		{"id":"img-var3-ad12","type":"file","file":"Elevate/00 Assets/T003/David_Ad_12/Var3/variant-1.png","x":2900,"y":660,"width":399,"height":500},
		{"id":"img-var1-ad22","type":"file","file":"Elevate/00 Assets/T003/Maria_Ad_22/Var1/variant-1.png","x":4000,"y":660,"width":399,"height":500},
		{"id":"text-var1-ad22","type":"text","text":"**Variation 1**\nPersona Life (Native): Supportive standing shoes by door, heavy school bag.","x":4000,"y":1180,"width":400,"height":100},
		{"id":"img-var2-ad22","type":"file","file":"Elevate/00 Assets/T003/Maria_Ad_22/Var2/variant-1.png","x":4450,"y":660,"width":399,"height":500},
		{"id":"text-var2-ad22","type":"text","text":"**Variation 2**\nMessage-Direct: Close-up of feet in comfortable shoes walking on tile.","x":4450,"y":1180,"width":400,"height":100},
		{"id":"img-var3-ad22","type":"file","file":"Elevate/00 Assets/T003/Maria_Ad_22/Var3/variant-1.png","x":4900,"y":660,"width":399,"height":500},
		{"id":"img-var1-ad21","type":"file","file":"Elevate/00 Assets/T003/Maria_Ad_21/Var1/variant-1.png","x":4000,"y":-440,"width":399,"height":500},
		{"id":"text-var2-ad12","type":"text","text":"**Variation 2**\nMessage-Direct: Blurry pharmacy sign visible through a car’s rainy windshield.","x":2450,"y":1180,"width":400,"height":100},
		{"id":"text-var3-ad12","type":"text","text":"**Variation 3: Weight Loss Cue**\\nMan struggling to button his suit jacket around his waist.","x":2900,"y":1180,"width":400,"height":100},
		{"id":"text-ad12","type":"text","text":"# Ad #12 — The Pharmacy Counter\n\nI stood at the pharmacy counter and felt the blood drain from my face.\n\n\"That'll be twelve hundred dollars,\" the pharmacist said, without looking up from his computer.\n\nI stared at the prescription my doctor had finally agreed to write for me.\n\nI’m a 45-year-old business owner. I’m used to solving problems.\n\nBut standing there, I felt completely powerless.\n\nMy insurance had denied the claim that morning, saying my health wasn't \"at risk enough\" yet.\n\nI walked out to my car and just sat there in the parking lot for ten minutes.\n\nI was worrying about my heart. I was worrying about not being around for my three kids.\n\nI’ve tried every \"fad\" diet that my employees mentioned. \n\nI’ve spent thousands on \"weight loss\" pills from the drugstore that did nothing but make my heart race.\n\nI felt like I was failing my family. I was building a business, but I couldn't even fix my own health.\n\nThen I reached out to a buddy from my business mastermind group.\n\nHe told me he’d found Elevate and that I could bypass the insurance red tape entirely.\n\nI did the medical review on my phone that afternoon while sitting in my car.\n\nIt was 100% online. A licensed provider reviewed my medical history and designed a plan just for me.\n\nNo waiting rooms. No insurance agents telling me I wasn't \"sick enough\" for help.\n\nThe medication and supplies were delivered discreetly to my door a few days later.\n\nThe first results moment happened about ten days in.\n\nI woke up and realized the \"food noise\"—the constant mental loop of thinking about lunch—was gone.\n\nI felt a level of focus at the office that I hadn't felt in a decade.\n\nI felt \"lighter\" on my feet. I didn't feel like I was dragging myself through the day anymore.\n\nLast night, I played tag with my kids in the backyard until the sun went down.\n\nI didn't need a break. I didn't feel like my heart was going to jump out of my chest.\n\nI realized I was spending more on entertaining clients than I was on my own longevity.\n\nNow, I have a professional medical plan for $58 a week. \n\nI used Afterpay to start for $0 down.\n\nDon't let insurance dictate your quality of life. \n\nSee if you're eligible for the support you actually need.\n\n[Link: See if you qualify]","x":1540,"y":660,"width":400,"height":880},
		{"id":"text-ad22","type":"text","text":"# Ad #22 — The Comfortable Shoes\n\nI realized I had bought a size I never thought I’d see in my closet.\n\nI was 51, a teacher of 25 years, and I felt like my body had betrayed me.\n\nIt wasn't that I was lazy. I spend eight hours a day on my feet.\n\nBut menopause hit, and it felt like my metabolism just went on strike.\n\nI avoid every staff photo. I stay in the back of the room during assemblies. \n\nI felt like I was disappearing, but in all the wrong ways.\n\nI tried the \"hormone\" supplements. I tried the extreme low-carb diets. \n\nI was hungry, I was tired, and the scale wouldn't move an inch.\n\nI felt like a failure. I was teaching my students about progress, but I couldn't make any of my own.\n\nThen I saw a post from a fellow educator who found Elevate.\n\nShe told me it was a medical approach that bypassed the willpower struggle entirely.\n\nI did the medical review on my phone while waiting for my car to warm up.\n\nIt was 100% online. A licensed provider reviewed my history and created a personalized plan.\n\nNo insurance red tape. No pharmacy counters.\n\nEverything arrived discreetly at my door a few days later.\n\nThe first change wasn't what I expected. It was the quiet in my head.\n\nThe \"food noise\"—the mental obsession with what I’d eat after work—just stopped.\n\nI felt in control for the first time in years.\n\nI felt \"lighter\" on my feet during my afternoon classes.\n\nYesterday, I actually wore a fitted blazer to school. \n\nI didn't feel like I had to hide. I felt like a leader again.\n\nI was wasting hundreds of dollars on supplements that did nothing.\n\nNow, my professional care plan is $58 a week. \n\nI used Afterpay to start for $0 down.\n\nIt wasn't a lack of discipline. It was my biology.\n\nSee if you're eligible for medical support today.\n\n[Link: See if you qualify]","x":3540,"y":660,"width":400,"height":880},
		{"id":"text-var3-ad22","type":"text","text":"**Variation 3: Weight Loss Cue**\\nWoman struggling to zip up a dress in a dimly lit fitting room.","x":4900,"y":1180,"width":400,"height":100},
		{"id":"text-ad21","type":"text","text":"# Ad #21 — The Classroom Desk\n\nI’ve taught high school history for 25 years, but I couldn't learn how to fix my own metabolism.\n\nI’m 51. I know how to research, I know how to follow a plan, and I know how to work hard.\n\nBut about three years ago, it felt like my body just stopped listening to me.\n\nThe \"incident\" happened in the middle of a parent-teacher conference.\n\nI was sitting there, trying to talk about a student's progress, and all I could think about was the bag of pretzels in my bottom drawer.\n\nI felt so ashamed. I was a professional, yet I was being held hostage by \"food noise\" while I was trying to do my job.\n\nThat night, I went home and realized I had bought a clothing size I never thought I’d see in my closet.\n\nI sat on the floor of my bedroom and felt like I was losing my identity.\n\nI tried Weight Watchers for the fourth time. I tried those expensive \"hormone balancing\" teas. \n\nI even tried extreme calorie counting, which just left me irritable and exhausted by second period.\n\nI felt like I was failing. I thought I was just meant to be \"the tired teacher\" for the rest of my career.\n\nThen I read a review from another teacher who described hitting the exact same \"biological wall\" at 50.\n\nShe mentioned Elevate and how it addressed the biology of the problem, not just the willpower.\n\nI took the quiz at my desk during my lunch break.\n\nThe medical review was 100% online. A licensed provider reviewed my history and designed a personalized care plan.\n\nThe medication and supplies were delivered discreetly to my house.\n\nThe first results moment happened about a week in.\n\nI was in the middle of a lecture on the Renaissance and I realized I hadn't thought about food once.\n\nThe \"obsession\" just stopped. I felt a mental clarity I hadn't felt in a decade.\n\nI felt in control of my body and my day.\n\nLast week, I actually stood in front of the classroom with passion again.\n\nI wasn't hiding behind my desk or wearing oversized cardigans to cover up.\n\nI realized I was spending so much money on \"quick fixes\" and teas that did nothing.\n\nNow, I have a professional medical plan for $58 a week. \n\nI used Afterpay to start for $0 down.\n\nIf you’ve hit a wall and \"trying harder\" isn't working, it’s not your fault.\n\nSee if you're eligible for the support your biology actually needs.\n\n[Link: See if you qualify]","x":3540,"y":-440,"width":400,"height":880},
		{"id":"text-var1-ad21","type":"text","text":"**Variation 1**\nPersona Life (Native): Overhead shot of teacher desk: papers, red pen, water.","x":4000,"y":80,"width":400,"height":100},
		{"id":"img-var2-ad21","type":"file","file":"Elevate/00 Assets/T003/Maria_Ad_21/Var2/variant-1.png","x":4450,"y":-440,"width":399,"height":500},
		{"id":"text-var2-ad21","type":"text","text":"**Variation 2**\nMessage-Direct: Close-up of a half-open desk drawer with a hidden snack bag.","x":4450,"y":80,"width":400,"height":100},
		{"id":"text-ad11","type":"text","text":"# Ad #11 — The Insurance Denial\n\nMy insurance agent told me my health wasn't \"a priority\" for coverage.\n\nI was sitting in my home office, staring at a stack of invoices, when I got the call.\n\nI’d just been to my doctor, and for the first time in years, I was ready to take my health seriously.\n\nBut the person on the other end of the line just saw a balance sheet.\n\nHe told me that because I didn't have \"secondary complications\" yet, they wouldn't cover the treatment my doctor recommended.\n\nI hung up the phone and felt a wave of frustration I hadn't felt in a long time.\n\nI’m 45. I’ve built a successful business from nothing. I employ twenty people.\n\nBut when it came to my own body, I felt like I was losing a game where the rules kept changing.\n\nThe real blow came at the pharmacy counter later that afternoon.\n\nI handed over the prescription my doctor had written, thinking I’d just pay out of pocket if I had to.\n\nThe pharmacist didn't even look up when he said, \"That’ll be twelve hundred dollars.\"\n\nI walked out of there without the medication and with a heavy pit in my stomach.\n\nI started worrying about my heart. About being there to see my three kids graduate.\n\nI tried the fad diets. I tried the \"weight loss\" pills from the drugstore that just made me jittery.\n\nI felt like a failure. I was winning at work but losing everywhere else.\n\nThen I was at a mastermind group meeting with my buddy Mark.\n\nHe looked different. Sharper. Lighter.\n\nHe told me he’d bypassed the insurance red tape entirely with Elevate.\n\nIt was a 100% online medical review. No waiting rooms. No insurance agents telling you what you’re worth.\n\nI took the quiz on my phone that night. It took two minutes.\n\nA licensed provider reviewed my history and designed a personalized care plan for me.\n\nThe medication and supplies were delivered right to my door.\n\nThe first change happened about a week in.\n\nThe \"food noise\"—the constant mental obsession with my next meal—just stopped.\n\nI felt a mental clarity I hadn't experienced in years.\n\nI felt \"lighter\" on my feet during my morning walk.\n\nLast Saturday, I spent three hours playing catch in the yard with my kids.\n\nI wasn't the dad sitting on the porch catching his breath. I was in the game.\n\nI realized I was spending more on business lunches in a week than this program costs.\n\nNow, my care plan is $58 a week. I started for $0 down with Afterpay.\n\nDon't let an insurance company decide your future.\n\nCheck your eligibility in two minutes and see if you qualify.\n\n[Link: See if you qualify]","x":1540,"y":-440,"width":400,"height":880},
		{"id":"text-ad25","type":"text","text":"# Ad #25 — The Grading Lamp\n\nThe constant \"food noise\" during my third-period class was the breaking point.\n\nI was supposed to be explaining the French Revolution, but my brain was stuck on the donuts in the faculty lounge.\n\nI’m 51. I’ve been a teacher for 25 years. I’m supposed to be in control of my classroom.\n\nBut I wasn't in control of my own mind. \n\nI felt \"heavy.\" I felt like menopause had rewritten the rules of my metabolism overnight.\n\nI’d tried everything. The points systems, the \"detox\" shakes, the extreme fasting.\n\nI was always hungry, always irritable, and always defeated.\n\nI felt like a failure. I was coaching my students to never give up, but I was ready to quit on myself.\n\nThen I read a review from another teacher who felt that exact same \"biological wall\" at 50.\n\nShe mentioned Elevate and the provider-led care they offer.\n\nI took the quiz on my phone during my 20-minute lunch break.\n\nThe medical review was 100% online. No extra appointments.\n\nA licensed provider reviewed my history and created a personalized plan for my body.\n\nThe medication and supplies were delivered discreetly to my door.\n\nThe first results moment happened during that same third-period class.\n\nI realized I hadn't thought about food once since breakfast.\n\nThe obsession was gone. I felt a mental clarity I hadn't felt in years.\n\nI felt \"lighter\" on my feet. My energy stayed steady all the way to the final bell.\n\nLast week, I actually stood in the center of the room to lead a debate. \n\nI wasn't hiding behind my desk anymore. I was teaching with passion.\n\nI realized I was spending so much money on \"quick fixes\" that did nothing.\n\nNow, my care plan is $58 a week. I started for $0 down.\n\nIf you’re doing everything \"right\" and the scale won't budge, it might be biological.\n\nCheck your eligibility today.\n\n[Link: See if you qualify]","x":3540,"y":3960,"width":400,"height":880},
		{"id":"text-ad23","type":"text","text":"# Ad #23 — The Lunch Break\n\nThe constant \"food noise\" during my third-period class was the breaking point.\n\nI was supposed to be explaining the French Revolution, but my brain was stuck on the donuts in the faculty lounge.\n\nI’m 51. I’ve been a teacher for 25 years. I’m supposed to be in control of my classroom.\n\nBut I wasn't in control of my own mind. \n\nI felt \"heavy.\" I felt like menopause had rewritten the rules of my metabolism overnight.\n\nI’d tried everything. The points systems, the \"detox\" shakes, the extreme fasting.\n\nI was always hungry, always irritable, and always defeated.\n\nI felt like a failure. I was coaching my students to never give up, but I was ready to quit on myself.\n\nThen I read a review from another teacher who felt that exact same \"biological wall\" at 50.\n\nShe mentioned Elevate and the provider-led care they offer.\n\nI took the quiz on my phone during my 20-minute lunch break.\n\nThe medical review was 100% online. No extra appointments.\n\nA licensed provider reviewed my history and created a personalized plan for my body.\n\nThe medication and supplies were delivered discreetly to my door.\n\nThe first results moment happened during that same third-period class.\n\nI realized I hadn't thought about food once since breakfast.\n\nThe obsession was gone. I felt a mental clarity I hadn't felt in years.\n\nI felt \"lighter\" on my feet. My energy stayed steady all the way to the final bell.\n\nLast week, I actually stood in the center of the room to lead a debate. \n\nI wasn't hiding behind my desk anymore. I was teaching with passion.\n\nI realized I was spending so much money on \"quick fixes\" that did nothing.\n\nNow, my care plan is $58 a week. I started for $0 down.\n\nIf you’re doing everything \"right\" and the scale won't budge, it might be biological.\n\nCheck your eligibility today.\n\n[Link: See if you qualify]","x":3540,"y":1760,"width":400,"height":880},
